{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640956"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17851"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17851"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.27,0,0.09,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10565"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78565"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10565"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17851"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63907"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10053"},{"type":"tags","id":"10056"},{"type":"tags","id":"10061"},{"type":"tags","id":"10063"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24639"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78565"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECellular metabolism is tightly regulated to maintain energy homeostasis. High-energy molecules like ATP can influence enzyme activity through allosteric regulation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following enzymes is allosterically inhibited by ATP?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pyruvate dehydrogenase in pyruvate oxidation","Isocitrate dehydrogenase in the citric acid cycle","Alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase in the citric acid cycle","Citrate synthase in the citric acid cycle","Hexokinase in glycolysis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EATP acts as an allosteric inhibitor of \u003Cstrong\u003Eisocitrate dehydrogenase in the citric acid cycle\u003C/strong\u003E. When ATP levels are high, the activity of isocitrate dehydrogenase is reduced, slowing down the citric acid cycle and conserving energy. This feedback regulation helps balance energy production with cellular energy needs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyruvate dehydrogenase in pyruvate oxidation\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme is regulated by phosphorylation/dephosphorylation, not by direct ATP binding\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase in the citric acid cycle\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme is regulated by the ATP/ADP ratio but not through direct ATP binding\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECitrate synthase in the citric acid cycle\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme is inhibited by citrate and ATP/ADP ratio but not directly by ATP\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHexokinase in glycolysis\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme is inhibited by its product glucose-6-phosphate, not by ATP\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis allosteric regulation is an example of negative feedback control in metabolism, where end products inhibit their own production pathway.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["ATP is an allosteric inhibitor of isocitrate dehydrogenase in the citric acid cycle, reducing its activity when ATP levels are high.","ATP does not directly inhibit other key metabolic enzymes like pyruvate dehydrogenase or alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase.","Allosteric regulation helps maintain energy homeostasis by adjusting metabolic flux based on cellular ATP levels."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63907"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17851"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63907"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T15:27:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T15:27:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10565"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78565"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and ret